What is advanced protein family enrichment analysis (Advanced PFE)?

Proteomics experiments often involve study of multiple conditions, for example, impact of drug treatment on wild type cells (case 1) and mutated cells (case 2). WT+treatment versus WT-treatment gives information about the effect of treatment on WT cells, while MUT+treatment versus MUT-treatment gives information of the effect on mutated cells. Each of these cases can be used as an input file for any of the aforementioned analys3s and visualizations; however, to analyze the difference of treatment outcomes between MUT and WT, which is especially important in cancer related research, MUT+treatment versus WT-treatment could be the most important study case. The protein family enrichment analysis (PFE) can be applied in order to 1) easily identify protein families (of enriched genes) that are different in the two conditions and 2) reduce false positives by excluding genes that were not enriched in control conditions.

PFE is performed by

1. finding significantly enriched genes in WT+treatment versus WT-treatment (family A, left panel, proteins shown in green) and in MUT+treatment versus MUT-treatment (family B, right panel, proteins shown in green)



2. excluding genes present in both lists, which represent false positives if someone is interested in differences between cases, not proteins enriched in both cases (enriched genes unique to family A are schematically presented in yellow, enriched genes unique to family B are schematically presented in red, enriched genes shared between families A and B are shown in orange)



3. overlaying remaining genes in both families (using different shapes and colours) on the volcano plot for MUT+treatment versus WT+treatment data

4. finding which genes from lists A and B are also enriched on the volcano plot: list A on the side of WT+treatment, list B on the side of MUT+treatment.
